{"title_page": "Trentem\u00f8ller", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Trentem\u00f8ller\n| image = Anders Trentem\u00f8ller Portrait 2014.jpg\n| caption = Trentem\u00f8ller (by Jonas Bang, 2014)\n| image_size = \n| landscape = yes\n| background = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name = Anders Trentem\u00f8ller\n| alias = Businessman<br />P.O.Q<br />Run Jeremy\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1972|10|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Vordingborg]], [[Denmark]]\n| origin = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| instrument = \n| genre = [[Alternative rock]] <br/>[[Indietronica]] <br/>[[Rock music|Rock]]<br />[[Electronica]]<br />[[Krautrock|Kraut]]<br />[[Gothic rock|Goth]]<br/>[[Ambient music|Ambient]]\n| occupation = [[Musician]] <br/>[[Record producer|Producer]] <br/>[[Composer]]\n| years_active = 1997&ndash;present\n| label = In My Room<br />Poker Flat Recordings<br />Audiomatique <br /> hfn music\n| website = {{URL|http://www.trentemoller.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Anders Trentem\u00f8ller''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8\u0251n\u0250s \u02c8ts\u02b0\u0281\u0251nt\u0259\u02ccm\u00f8\u02c0l\u0250|lang}}; born 16 October 1972) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[independent music|indie]]/[[electronic music]] composer, producer and multi-instrumentalist based in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]].\n\n==History==\nAnders Trentem\u00f8ller is a Copenhagen-based musician, composer and producer who started in the late 1990s with different indie rock projects.  In 2006, following a line of more electronic orientated 12-inch  EPs, Trentem\u00f8ller released his debut album ''[[The Last Resort (album)|The Last Resort]]''. In 2007 he assembled his first full live band, with [[Henrik Vibskov]] on drums and [[Mikael Simpson]] on guitar. Complete with visuals from director Karim Ghahwagi, the ensuing \u2018Trentem\u00f8ller: Live In Concert\u2019 tour brought him to the United States for the first time as well as to festivals including [[Glastonbury Festival|Glastonbury]] (UK), [[Roskilde Festival|Roskilde]] (Denmark) and [[Melt! Festival|Melt!]] (Germany).\n\nIn 2009, ''[[The Trentem\u00f8ller Chronicles]]'', a double compilation of unreleased songs, non-album tracks and remixes for acts including [[R\u00f6yksopp]], [[Moby]] and [[The Knife]], was released. He also headlined the Orange Stage at Roskilde Festival, playing in front of 60,000 people, with a set design created by Vibskov.\n\nAfter starting up his own record label, In My Room, Trentem\u00f8ller\u2019s second album ''[[Into the Great Wide Yonder]]'' was released in 2010. It was a move into a more analogue sound influenced by indie and post punk, and incorporating more live instrumentation and vocals. Expanding his live band to seven people, he continued to tour around the world for two years. His appearance at 2011\u2019s [[Coachella Festival]] was described by ''[[NME]]'' as \u201cone of the biggest breakouts of Coachella,\u201d saying he \u201cstunned all onlookers and became the toast of the fest.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|title=Coachella 2011 - The 12 Most Memorable Moments|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/coachella-2011-the-12-most-memorable-moments|website=Nme.com|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> Trentem\u00f8ller toured widely across the US and appeared on [[Carson Daly]]. The world tour ended with two shows in [[Freetown Christiania|Christiania]], Copenhagen, released as the live album ''Live In Copenhagen''.\n\nFollowing his second album, ''Reworked/Remixed'' was released, a compilation of Trentem\u00f8ller\u2019s remixes for other artists and other musicians' reworking of his music including [[Modeselektor]], [[UNKLE]], [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand]], [[Andrew Weatherall]], [[Efterklang]] and [[Depeche Mode]]. Trentem\u00f8ller\u2019s music has also been used by film directors, including [[Oliver Stone]] (''[[Savages (2012 film)|Savages]]''), [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]] (''[[The Skin I Live In]]''), and [[Jacques Audiard]] (''[[Rust and Bone]]'').\n\nIn September 2013, Trentem\u00f8ller released his third full-length album ''[[Lost (Trentem\u00f8ller album)|Lost]]'', including collaborations with [[Low (band)|Low]], Jonny Pierce from [[The Drums]], Marie Fisker, Kazu Makino of [[Blonde Redhead]], Jana Hunter of [[Lower Dens]], [[Ghost Society]] and Sune Wagner of [[The Raveonettes]]. That year, Trentem\u00f8ller also supported [[Depeche Mode]] on their [[Delta Machine]] world tour and appeared at Melt!, Dour, Pitch and Zurich Open Air. In 2014 Trentem\u00f8ller composed the theme for the [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] series ''[[Halt and Catch Fire (TV series)|Halt and Catch Fire]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artofthetitle.com/title/halt-and-catch-fire/|title=Halt and Catch Fire|website=Artofthetitle.com|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> In 2014, ''Lost'' was awarded a silver certification from the [[Independent Music Companies Association]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impalamusic.org/sites/default/files/pictures/Awards5.png|title=Chart|website=Impalamusic.org|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref> which indicated sales of at least 20,000 copies throughout Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.impalamusic.org/node/340|title=IMPALA Awards for European Independent Acts Hit Record Levels - Impala|website=Impalamusic.org|accessdate=19 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nTrentem\u00f8ller's fourth album, ''Fixion''{{circular reference|date=April 2018}}, was released on 16 September 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/dance/7416460/trentemoller-on-his-new-record-fixion-premieres-river-in-me-feat-jehnny|title=Trentemoller on His New Record 'Fixion,' Premieres 'River In Me' feat. Jehnny Beth: Exclusive|last=Flanagan|first=Andrew|website=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref> It featured vocals by Marie Fisker, Lisbet Fritze and [[Savages (band)|Jehnny Beth]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/fixion-mw0002955557|title=Fixion - Trentem\u00f8ller {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits|last=Monger|first=Timothy|date=|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=2016-09-22}}</ref>\n\nTrentem\u00f8ller has collaborated numerously with Swedish contemporary artist [[Andreas Emenius]], who directed the music videos ''Complicated'' 2016, ''Redefine'' 2016, ''Come Undone'' 2014, and ''Deceive'' 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://imvdb.com/n/andreas-emenius|title=Andreas Emenius|website=IMVDb|language=en|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref> \n\nHis album ''Obverse'' has been nominated for [[Independent Music Companies Association|IMPALA]]'s European Independent Album of the Year Award (2019).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.impalamusic.org/content/22-nominees-shortlisted-impala%E2%80%99s-european-independent-album-year-award|title=22 nominees shortlisted for IMPALA\u2019s European Independent Album of the Year Award {{!}} Impala|website=www.impalamusic.org|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n==Style and influences==\nTrentem\u00f8ller's later music has been described as synthwave and [[pop (music)|pop]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.treblezine.com/reviews/32035-trentemoller-fixion-review/ |title= Trentem\u00f8ller : Fixion |work= treblezine.com |date= 30 September 2016 }}</ref> His early tracks (especially The Last Resort) show influences drawing from early downtempo and trip hop, minimal, glitch, and darkwave with an often cinematic feel. He cited amongst his influences [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[My Bloody Valentine (band)|My Bloody Valentine]], [[Slowdive]], [[Joy Division]],<ref>{{cite |url=http://blog.lesoir.be/frontstage/2016/09/17/des-voix-dans-la-machine/ |title= Trentem\u00f8ller: des voix dans la machine |work=Lesoir.be |date=17 September 2016 |first=Didier |last=Stiers |accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref> and [[Depeche Mode]].<ref>{{cite |url= http://www.lesinrocks.com/musique/critique-album/trentemoller-joue-carte-tenebreuse-nouvel-album-fixion/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160916202320/http://www.lesinrocks.com/musique/critique-album/trentemoller-joue-carte-tenebreuse-nouvel-album-fixion/ |url-status= dead |archive-date= 16 September 2016 |title=Trentem\u00f8ller joue la carte t\u00e9n\u00e9breuse dans son nouvel album |work=Lesinrocks.com |date= 9 September 2016 |accessdate=17 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:10px;\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:170px;\"| Album\n! colspan=\"8\" style=\"text-align:center; width:20px;\"| Peak positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center; width:70px;\"| Certification\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Tracklisten|DEN]]<br><ref name=\"den\">{{cite web | url=http://danishcharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Trentem%F8ller | title= Trentem\u00f8ller discography | publisher=Hung Medien | website=Danishcharts.com |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[\u00d63 Austria Top 40|AUT]]<br><ref name=\"aut\">{{cite web | url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Trentem%F8ller | title= Trentem\u00f8ller discography | publisher=Hung Medien | website=Austriancharts.at |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL <br>(Fl)]]<br><ref name=\"fl\">{{cite web | url=http://ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Trentem%F8ller | title= Trentem\u00f8ller discography | publisher=Hung Medien | website=Ultratop.be |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL <br>(Wa)]]<br><ref name=\"wa\">{{cite web | url=http://ultratop.be/fr/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Trentem%F8ller | title= Trentem\u00f8ller discography | publisher=Hung Medien | website=Ultratop.be |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[SNEP|FRA]]<br><ref name=\"fr\">{{cite web | url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Trentem%F8ller | title= Trentem\u00f8ller discography | publisher=Hung Medien | website=Lescharts.com |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[GfK Entertainment Charts|GER]]<br /><ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web|url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/suche?artistId=Trentem\u00f8ller|title=Discographie von Trentem\u00f8ller|publisher=GfK Entertainment|accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[MegaCharts|NL]]<br>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Swiss Hitparade|SWI]]<br><ref name=\"swi\">{{cite web | url=http://hitparade.ch/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Trentem%F8ller | title= Trentem\u00f8ller discography | publisher=Hung Medien | website=Hitparade.ch |accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2006\n| ''[[The Last Resort (album)|The Last Resort]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 62\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 148\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2010\n| ''[[Into the Great Wide Yonder]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 27\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 79\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 142\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 37\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 86\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 41\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"2\"| 2013\n| ''Live in Copenhagen'' \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n| s