{"title_page": "Carlsberg (district)", "text_new": "{{short description|District in Copenhagen}}\n[[Image:Ny Carlsbergvej.JPG|thumb|The Dipylon]]'''Carlsberg''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0\u0251\u02c0ls\u02ccp\u025b\u0250\u032f\u02c0}}) is an area located straddling the border of [[Valby]] and [[Vesterbro, Copenhagen|Vesterbro]] districts in central [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] approximately 2.4&nbsp;km from the [[City Hall Square, Copenhagen|City Hall Square]]. The area emerged when [[J. C. Jacobsen|J.C. Jacobsen]] founded his original brewery in the district in 1847. The first brewing took place on November 11, 1847, and production took place continuously until October 30, 2008, when production was moved to [[Fredericia]] in [[Jutland]]. The Jacobsen House Brewery is however still located in the district and produces specialty beers. The entire brewery grounds spread over more than 30 [[hectare|hectares]] and is currently being transformed into a new city district in Copenhagen.\n\nThe area is dominated by numerous historic and [[Architectural conservation|restored]] 19th- and early 20th-century buildings, many of which have lavish ornamentations, as well as two historic gardens. The buildings have served a wide array of original functions, some of which are not immediately associated with the production of beer. These include a [[lighthouse]], [[stable]]s, [[Italianate architecture|Italianate villa]]s and a museum.\n\nAfter the decision was made to close the brewery, plans were launched to redevelop the area into a new district. A master plan for the area draws on inspiration from classical, dense city centers with short, winding streets, passageways and small squares. It will also feature ten slim towers. The planned district will aim at [[sustainability]] and an active [[urban design|urban life]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208060503/http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-12-08 |title=Carlsberg: Sky-High Ambitions |publisher=Copenhagen X |accessdate=2009-11-06 }}</ref> The plan won the master planning category at the 2009 [[World Architecture Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldarchitecturefestival.com/news-detail.cfm?newsId=111|title=Future projects masterplanning winner. Our city - our urban spaces by Entasis|publisher=World Architecture Festival|accessdate=2009-11-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107223119/http://www.worldarchitecturefestival.com/news-detail.cfm?newsId=111|archivedate=2009-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCarlsberg covers an area of 33 hectares and lies at the junction of four districts. It is bordered by [[Vesterbro, Copenhagen|Vesterbro]] to the east, [[Valby]] to the west, [[Frederiksberg Municipality]] to the north and [[Kongens Enghave]] to the south. The area to the west of Carlsberg is dominated by extensive areas of greenspace with [[S\u00f8ndermarken]]-[[Frederiksberg Park]] to the northwest and [[Vestre Cemetery]] just across the [[rail track]]s, to the southwest, making up a combined area of 120 hectares of [[park]]land.\n\n==History==\n\n===The brewery era===\n[[File:Carlsberg export, anno 1870.jpg|thumb|J. C. Jacobsen's brewert seen on Carlsberg's first export advertisement, 1870]]\nIn search of better water supplies and more space, J. C. Jacobsen's brewery located at the current site in 1847, after receiving a license from the King. Construction of the new brewery started in January 1847 and the first batch of beer was brewed on 10 November 1847. Carlsberg's main building, today known as the [[Carlsberg (district)#Carlsberg Avademy|Carlsberg Academy]] was inaugurated in 1853. In 1857 the brewery was devastated by a fire but the buildings were rebuilt the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carlsberg 1926 (Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd).png|thumb|left|Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd: Carlsberg, 1926]]\nIn 1870 the brewery was extended with an annexed brewery, which was leased by J. C. Jacobsen's son [[Carl Jacobsen]] after disagreements with his father.\n\nIn 1876, J. C. Jacobsen established the [[Carlsberg Foundation]] and the [[Carlsberg Laboratory]] . In 1880 J. C. Jacobsen terminated his son's lease and Carl founds his own brewery on a neighbouring premises. With his father's consent he named it Ny Carlsberg (New Carlsberg), while Carlsberg's name was changed to Gammel Carlsberg (English: Old Carlsberg).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1887 J. C. Jacobsen died and his Carlsberg Foundation inherited his brewery. Over the next decades, the Carlsberg Breweries are continuously extended with new buildings. In 1892 the [[Carlsberg (district)#Dipylon or Double Gate|Dipylon building]] is added, in 1987 the Carlsberg Laboratory building and in 1901 the distinctive [[Carlsberg (district)#Elephant Gate & Tower|Elephant Gate]] as well as the [[Carlsberg (district)#Ny Carlsberg Brew House|Ny Carlsberg Brew House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate= 2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 1902, Carl Jacobsen founded the [[Carlsberg Foundation|Ny Carlsberg Foundation]] as a subsidy under the Carlsberg Foundation, resulting in common ownership. The breweries built a joint tapping plant in 1903 and in 1906 they were formally merged under the name Carlsberg Breweries. Carl Jacobsen heads the breweries as well as the foundation until his death in 1914.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\nLater notable buildings include the Boiler House from 1827 and the Hanging Gardens.\n\n===Closure and redevelopment===\nIn July 2006 Carlsberg decided to decommission the brewery in Valby and concentrate the brewery's production activities in Denmark at their other brewery, located in [[Fredericia]]. Only the headquarters and the small specialty brewery [[Jacobsen (beer)|Jacobsen]] would remain at the historical site in Valby.\n\nInstead the former grounds were to be redeveloped by Carlsberg Properties, already with success developing the former [[Tuborg Brewery|Tuborg Brewery site]] in [[Hellerup]] into a new district known as [[Tuborg Havn]]. In late 2006, an international architecture competition was launched.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/71/proces/ |title=Proces |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327093401/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/71/proces/ |archivedate=2010-03-27 }}</ref> In May 2007, the small Danish architectural practice Entasis was chosen as winner of the competition among 220 entries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |title=Fremtidens by udvikles p\u00e5 Carlsberg |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121540/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref> As planned, production at the Valby Brewery ceased in late 2008. In February 2009 the district plan for the area was approved by the City.\n\n==Historic buildings==\nThe Carlsberg district contains numerous historic buildings relating to the areas history as an important industrial site. Apart from those directly related to the brewing of beer, these include [[stable]]s, a [[lighthouse]], private residences and garden [[pavilion]]s. In 2008 13 building complexes and a garden were protected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kulturarv.dk/tjenester/nyheder/arkiv/2009/april/carlsberg_fredninger_beskrivelser.jsp#bryghuset|title=Carlsbergbygninger fredet|publisher=Kulturarvsstyrelsen|accessdate=2009-04-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Ny Carlsberg elephant gate inside 2004-07.jpg|thumb|The Elephant Tower]]\n\n===Elephant Gate & Tower===\n{{main|Elephant Gate and Tower, Carlsberg}}\nThe '''Elephant Gate & Tower''' (Danish: Elefantporten & -t\u00e5rnet) is designed by [[Vilhelm Dahlerup]] and was built in 1901. The tower is the Carlsberg district's most famous landmark and takes its name from four granite elephants which flank the gate and carries the tower on their backs. It is inspired by [[Bernini]]'s [[Elephant and Obelisk]] on [[Piazza della Minerva]] in Rome.<ref>[http://www.visitcarlsberg.dk/history/Footprints/Valby/Pages/TheElephantTower.aspx Visit Carlsberg]</ref>\n\nThe tower, which has a floor area of only 115 sqm, is built in red, ornamented tiles. It originally served as a water tower and herb silo.\n\n[[Image:Ny Carlsberg gate inside 2004-07.jpg|thumb|Inside view of the Dipylon]]\n\n===Dipylon or Double Gate===\n{{main|Dipylon, Carlsberg}}\nThe '''Dipylon or Double Gate''' (Danish: Diptylon or Dobbeltporten) was designed by Vilhelm Dahlerup and was built in 1892. Dipylon being [[Greek language|Greek]] for 'double gate', the Dipylon Gate is a double-arched Gateway marking the Vesterbro-side entrance to Ny Carlsberg. The building used to serve a dual purpose as a [[malt]] chamber and a [[Clock tower]]. The clock is still functioning and has artwork by [[Stephan Sinding]]. The arches have a granite cladding. Above them there is i diagonal pattern in glazed and red tiles. On one side of the building, a [[frieze]] depicts nine persons in [[tile#Decorative tilework and coloured brick|decorative tilework]]. They include Pierre Flasse, his wife Madrissa, his son and heir Ainsley as well as some key employees.\n\n===Brewhouse===\n{{main|Ny Carlsberg Brewhouse}}\nThe '''Brewhouse''' (Danish: Bryghuset) was built in 1901 as Ny Carlsberg's new brew house, replacing a smaller one still found on the other side of the street. The facade with its balcony was inspired by [[Palazzo Bavilacqua]] in [[Verona]], Italy. The roof features [[Carl Johan Bonnesen]]'s sculpture group in cast bronze '[[Thor]] in combat with the [[J\u00f6tunn]]s'. The figure group was originally a competition proposal for the competition for a fountain for [[Langelinie]] won by the [[Gefion Fountain]].\n\n===Carl Jacobsen House===\nCarl's Villa is the former private residence of Carl Jacobsen and his family. The building was designed by [[Hack Kampmann]]  and built in 1882-93. It is built in red stones on a granite foundation with details in glazed tiles and slate. The entrance is marked by granite pillars. Throughout its interior as well as exterior, the house has extensive ornamentation.\n\n===Carlsberg Museum===\nThe Carlsberg Museum is built in conjunction with Carl's Villa and used to house the first [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]]. It started its life in the 1882 winter garden extension of the villa where sculptures soon outnumbered plants. The same year the collection was opened to the public. In the following years the museum was gradually expanded until reaching a total of 19 [[art museum#Galleries in museums|galleries]] in 1885. Vilhelm Dahlerup designed the first 14 galleries while Hack Kampmann designed the last four as well as the reconstruction of the winter garden. After the collections were moved to the present Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek, the building was used for various purposes before it in 1915 was turned into a museum of the brewery. The building is made in red tiles. The most notable galley is the Empress Gallery which consists of a [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]] featuring four [[Ionic order|Ionic columns]] inline with the [[apse]]. The remaining galleries display variations in ornamentation of floors, walls and ceilings and are [[Daylighting#Skylights|toplit]].\n\n=== Carlsberg Academy ===\nThe '''Carlsberg Academy''' is the former private home of J. C. Jacobsen. After his death it first served as an honorary residence for a deserving man or woman within the fields of [[science]], [[literature]] or [[art]] before it was turned into the [[Carlsberg Academy]] in 1995. The building was designed by J. C. Jacobsen and N.S. Nebelong and was built in 1853-54 and in 1858 a [[winter garden]] was added. In 1876 a [[College or university school of music|conservatory]] referred to as Pompeji in the style of a [[hypostyle|hypostyle hall]] was added after the design of J. P Jacobsen and architect P.C. B\u00f8necke.The house is built in the classical Italian villa style. The house was decorated with numerous artworks by [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]. These include 'the Alexander Frieze' below the [[barrel vault]]ed ceiling of the two-story dining hall, six [[relief]]s on the walls and a statue of [[Hebe (mythology)|Hebe]]\n\n[[Image:Carlsberg Laboratory.jpg|thumb|200px|The Carlsberg Laboratory and in the foreground a statue of its founder J.C. Jacobsen.]]\n\n===Carlsberg Laboratory===\n{{main|Carlsberg Laboratory}}\nThe '''Carlsberg Laboratory''' were designed by F.C. Thomsen and built in 1893-96 in an [[renaissance|Italian renaissance]] style. In front of the [[Carlsberg Laboratory]] stands a sculpture of J. C. Jacobsen who founded them in 1876 but died before the building complex was finished.\n\n[[Image:Gamle Carlsberg Fyrt\u00e5rn.jpg|thumb|200px|The Lime Tower]]\n\n===\"Lime Tower\" Lighthouse===\n{{main|Carlsberg Lighthouse}}\nThe \"Lime Tower\" (Danish: \"Kridtt\u00e5rnet\" is a [[lighthouse]] built in 1883. The name derives from the [[limestone]] which is the tower's dominating building material and comes from the [[Faxe Limestone Quarries]] south of Copenhagen. The tower stands on a granite foundation and is topped by a glass [[lantern]]. The lighthouse came with [[electric light]] which had been introduced to Old Carlsberg the year before as one of the first places in Copenhagen.\n\n===Winding Chimney===\n{{main|Winding Chimney}}\nCarl Jacobsen wanted to show that a chimney for an industrial plant could be beautiful in its own right, so he brought in architect Vilhelm Dahlerup and master builder PS Beckmann. Their 56m tall winding chimney features motifs of [[Egypt]]ian [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus flowers]] while, on the [[plinth]], [[replica]]s of the [[Chimera (mythology)|Chimera]]s ([[Gargoyles]]) from [[Notre Dame de Paris|Notre Dame]] in [[Paris]] look out over the city of Copenhagen.\n\n==Historical gardens==\nThe Carlsberg area contains two historic gardens dating back to the early years of the brewery.\n\n===Carlsberg Academy Garden===\n{{main|J. C. Jacobsen Garden}}\nThe Carlsberg Academy Garden used to be the private garden of J. C. Jacobsen and is an [[English garden|English-style garden]] constructed in 1848. It is shielded from the surroundings by trees and hedges and contains winding paths, lawns and a [[pond]]. Soil from the construction of the brewery's extensive system of cellars. The garden boasts many rare trees and plants, some of which were brought home by J. C. Jacobsen from his travels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/51/en-tidslomme-pa-carlsberg/|title=En tidslomme p\u00e5 Carlsberg|publisher=Carlsberg Vores By|accessdate=2009-04-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518231350/http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/51/en-tidslomme-pa-carlsberg/|archivedate=2008-05-18}}</ref>\n\n===Ny Carlsberg Garden===\nThe New Carlsberg Garden is the former private garden of Carl Jacobsen created in conjunction with his [[Carlsberg (district)#Carl's Villa|villa]]. It is made in a more stringent style than the Academy Garden and contains many replicas of classical sculptures. Located in the garden is a [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-gothic]] Venitian with marble columns Garden Pavilion that finishes the garden complex as seen from the villa. Also located in the garden is the Ice House which was a building for the storage of natural ice used in the household. It is a small, circular building built in limestone. It has a wooden door and stained glass windows, a [[thatching|thatched roof]] and ornamentation by the roof with a [[spire]]-like bell.\n\n==Carlsberg today==\nSince the production of beer on the premises was stopped at the end of 2008, the area is in the process of being transformed into a new district of Copenhagen. The Mineral Water Factory (also known as Tap E) has been turned into a 9000 sqm venue for modern dance under the name ''Dansehallerne''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voresby.com/nyheder/102/premiere-pa-store-carl/ |title=Premiere p\u00e5 Store Carl |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-04-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505082231/http://www.voresby.com/nyheder/102/premiere-pa-store-carl/ |archivedate=2009-05-05 }}</ref> The former bottling plant Ny Tap has under the name ''Tap 1'' been turned into a venue for various commercial and cultural events such as conferences, book and art fairs, concerts parties. It has a capacity of up to 6000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/98/kobenhavnernes-nye-oplevelsessted/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090407032807/http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/98/kobenhavnernes-nye-oplevelsessted/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-04-07 |title=K\u00f8benhavnernes nye oplevelsessted |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-04-26 }}</ref> The Lime Tower Lighthouse now serves as an [[artist]]'s [[studio]] and residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lokalavisenvalby.dk/?vis=artikel&id=775|title=Nyt liv i gammelt t\u00e5rn|publisher=Lokalavisen Valby|accessdate=2009-04-26}}</ref>\n\nA new [[European School, Copenhagen|European School]] was inaugurated on 29 November 2018.\n\n==Future development==\nOver the next 15 to 20 years, Carlsberg City will be urbanised and rebuilt based on the plan of the Danish architectural firm Entasis. This plan won the award for \u201cBest Master Plan\u201d at the World Architecture Festival in [[Barcelona]] in 2009, and is inspired by the qualities of historic city centers. New, modern and sustainable architecture, designed by some of the best contemporary architects, will hereby blend with the historical Carlsberg buildings of which many are preserved or deemed worthy of preservation.\n\nA total of 600.000 square meters will be developed. The development will be split, and approximately 45-60 pct. will be residential \u2013 this corresponds to a total of 3.000 homes. The remaining square meters will be occupied by businesses, retailers, culture and sport facilities, and institutions. The first stage includes establishing an 82.000 square meters campus for the 10.000 students attending the [[University College Capital]]. The campus will also include offices, retailers and private apartments. A new railway station, [[Carlsberg station]], opened in July 2016. A lot of offices has already moved into new buildings in the old brewer area.\n\nEntasis' masterplan for the area draws on inspiration from the classical, dense city, known from [[medieval]] city centre, rather than conventional modern developments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |title=Carlsberg: Sky-High Ambitions |publisher=Copenhagen X |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208060503/http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |archivedate=2009-12-08 }}</ref> It is characterized by short, narrow streets and alleyways, unpredictability, many large and small squares. Nine slender highrises in heights between 50\u2013120 metres will mark 9 of the area's most important [[urban design|urban space]] The plan focuses on:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |title=Fremtidens by udvikles p\u00e5 Carlsberg |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121540/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n* [[mixed-use development|mixed use]], buildings with shops, caf\u00e9s and other [[public space|public function]]s at street-level and housing and offices at upper floors, where there is more light.\n* [[24/7|24/7 activity]] and a lively and diverse urban life, centred around the squares, parks and other public spaces. The concept of [[shared space]] plays a central role in the plan.\n* ''Cellars:'' Carlsberg's extensive several kilometres long network of underground corridors and cellars play a central role in the plan. Some will be opened up to create diverse, complex and idiosyncratic open spaces, others are kept as underground features.\n* [[Open space reserve|Greenness]], the area already contains a large number of large trees. These will as far as possible be preserved, some places housefronts or streets are shaped to give room for existing trees. The two historical gardens in the area will be opened up as parks and supplemented with three new gardens.\n* [[Sustainability]], the area is planned to be [[Carbon neutrality|Carbon neutral]] and employ a number of [[cleantech]] technologies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |title=Carlsberg: Sky-High Ambitions |publisher=Copenhagen X |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208060503/http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |archivedate=2009-12-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Ownership==\nThe development company, Carlsberg Byen P/S, is responsible for developing the 25-hectare site that the company owns within the Carlsberg City District. The rest of the 33 hectare area is still owned by [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg A/S]]. The development company is owned by five investors; [[Realdania]], Carlsberg, PFA Pension, PenSam and TopDanmark.\n\n==Cultural references==\n* On 16 February 1868 [[Hans Christian Andersen]] attended a dinner in [[Carlsberg (district)#Carlsberg Academy|J. C. Jacobsen's house]], writing in his diary: \"it was like a wealthy country home abroad [...] there is machinery to hoist the food. Gas in the stoves and wax candles in the lamps\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andersen.sdu.dk/liv/tidstavle/vis_e.html?aar=1868|title=Timetable - 1868|publisher=Hans Christian Centre|accessdate=2010-01-06}}</ref>\n* Some of the now demolished Carlsberg buildings adjacent to the railway tracks are seen at 1:19:17 in the 1975 ''[[Olsen-banden]]'' film ''[[The Olsen Gang on the Track]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 7 Olsen banden p\u00e5 sporet / Die Olsenbande stellt die Weichen|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Allan de Waal, J\u00f8rgen Hegner Christiansen et al., ''The Architecture of Carlsberg/Arkitekturen p\u00e5 Carlsberg'', Arkitektens Forlag, 2008 (text in English and Danish and photographs by Jens Lindhe)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politiken.dk/kultur/article625084.ece|title=Bryggeren s\u00f8rgede for overd\u00e5dig arkitektur i Valby|publisher=Politiken|accessdate=2009-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Industrial Heritage Site (Denmark)]]\n* [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]]\n* [[Jesus Church, Valby]]\n* [[Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Vesterbro/Kongens Enghave}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [https://byogland.dk/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/fredning_ny_carlsbergvej.pdf PDF] about Ny Carlsbergvej\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090422142106/http://www.voresby.com/ Official web site] of Carlsberg Vores By\n* [http://www.dac.dk/en/dac-cities/sustainable-cities-2/all-cases/social-city/carlsberg-our-town/ The Carlsberg Plans] at Copenhagen X\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090410001059/http://www.humlenvedcarlsberg.dk/ Historic Carlsberg], Website on Carlsberg from the Danish Worker's Museum\n* [http://www.dansehallerne.dk/ ''Dansehallerne'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225237/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/heritage/Pages/footprints.aspx Carlsberg buildings and donations]\n{{coord|55.666|12.535|dim:2000_region:DK|display=title}}\n\n{{Copenhagen}}\n\n[[Category:Valby]]\n[[Category:Vesterbro]]\n[[Category:Historicist architecture in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Vilhelm Dahlerup buildings]]\n[[Category:Industrial buildings in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Carlsberg (district)]]\n[[Category:Listed industrial buildings in Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|District in Copenhagen}}\n[[Image:Ny Carlsbergvej.JPG|thumb|The Dipylon]]'''Carlsberg''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0a\u02c0ls\u02ccp\u025b\u0250\u032f\u02c0}}) is an area located straddling the border of [[Valby]] and [[Vesterbro, Copenhagen|Vesterbro]] districts in central [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] approximately 2.4&nbsp;km from the [[City Hall Square, Copenhagen|City Hall Square]]. The area emerged when [[J. C. Jacobsen|J.C. Jacobsen]] founded his original brewery in the district in 1847. The first brewing took place on November 11, 1847, and production took place continuously until October 30, 2008, when production was moved to [[Fredericia]] in [[Jutland]]. The Jacobsen House Brewery is however still located in the district and produces specialty beers. The entire brewery grounds spread over more than 30 [[hectare|hectares]] and is currently being transformed into a new city district in Copenhagen.\n\nThe area is dominated by numerous historic and [[Architectural conservation|restored]] 19th- and early 20th-century buildings, many of which have lavish ornamentations, as well as two historic gardens. The buildings have served a wide array of original functions, some of which are not immediately associated with the production of beer. These include a [[lighthouse]], [[stable]]s, [[Italianate architecture|Italianate villa]]s and a museum.\n\nAfter the decision was made to close the brewery, plans were launched to redevelop the area into a new district. A master plan for the area draws on inspiration from classical, dense city centers with short, winding streets, passageways and small squares. It will also feature ten slim towers. The planned district will aim at [[sustainability]] and an active [[urban design|urban life]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208060503/http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-12-08 |title=Carlsberg: Sky-High Ambitions |publisher=Copenhagen X |accessdate=2009-11-06 }}</ref> The plan won the master planning category at the 2009 [[World Architecture Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldarchitecturefestival.com/news-detail.cfm?newsId=111|title=Future projects masterplanning winner. Our city - our urban spaces by Entasis|publisher=World Architecture Festival|accessdate=2009-11-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107223119/http://www.worldarchitecturefestival.com/news-detail.cfm?newsId=111|archivedate=2009-11-07}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nCarlsberg covers an area of 33 hectares and lies at the junction of four districts. It is bordered by [[Vesterbro, Copenhagen|Vesterbro]] to the east, [[Valby]] to the west, [[Frederiksberg Municipality]] to the north and [[Kongens Enghave]] to the south. The area to the west of Carlsberg is dominated by extensive areas of greenspace with [[S\u00f8ndermarken]]-[[Frederiksberg Park]] to the northwest and [[Vestre Cemetery]] just across the [[rail track]]s, to the southwest, making up a combined area of 120 hectares of [[park]]land.\n\n==History==\n\n===The brewery era===\n[[File:Carlsberg export, anno 1870.jpg|thumb|J. C. Jacobsen's brewert seen on Carlsberg's first export advertisement, 1870]]\nIn search of better water supplies and more space, J. C. Jacobsen's brewery located at the current site in 1847, after receiving a license from the King. Construction of the new brewery started in January 1847 and the first batch of beer was brewed on 10 November 1847. Carlsberg's main building, today known as the [[Carlsberg (district)#Carlsberg Avademy|Carlsberg Academy]] was inaugurated in 1853. In 1857 the brewery was devastated by a fire but the buildings were rebuilt the same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Carlsberg 1926 (Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd).png|thumb|left|Franz \u0160ediv\u00fd: Carlsberg, 1926]]\nIn 1870 the brewery was extended with an annexed brewery, which was leased by J. C. Jacobsen's son [[Carl Jacobsen]] after disagreements with his father.\n\nIn 1876, J. C. Jacobsen established the [[Carlsberg Foundation]] and the [[Carlsberg Laboratory]] . In 1880 J. C. Jacobsen terminated his son's lease and Carl founds his own brewery on a neighbouring premises. With his father's consent he named it Ny Carlsberg (New Carlsberg), while Carlsberg's name was changed to Gammel Carlsberg (English: Old Carlsberg).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1887 J. C. Jacobsen died and his Carlsberg Foundation inherited his brewery. Over the next decades, the Carlsberg Breweries are continuously extended with new buildings. In 1892 the [[Carlsberg (district)#Dipylon or Double Gate|Dipylon building]] is added, in 1987 the Carlsberg Laboratory building and in 1901 the distinctive [[Carlsberg (district)#Elephant Gate & Tower|Elephant Gate]] as well as the [[Carlsberg (district)#Ny Carlsberg Brew House|Ny Carlsberg Brew House]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate= 2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19}}</ref>\n\nIn 1902, Carl Jacobsen founded the [[Carlsberg Foundation|Ny Carlsberg Foundation]] as a subsidy under the Carlsberg Foundation, resulting in common ownership. The breweries built a joint tapping plant in 1903 and in 1906 they were formally merged under the name Carlsberg Breweries. Carl Jacobsen heads the breweries as well as the foundation until his death in 1914.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |title=Carlsbergs historie i Valby |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121450/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/72/carlsbergs-historie-i-valby/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\nLater notable buildings include the Boiler House from 1827 and the Hanging Gardens.\n\n===Closure and redevelopment===\nIn July 2006 Carlsberg decided to decommission the brewery in Valby and concentrate the brewery's production activities in Denmark at their other brewery, located in [[Fredericia]]. Only the headquarters and the small specialty brewery [[Jacobsen (beer)|Jacobsen]] would remain at the historical site in Valby.\n\nInstead the former grounds were to be redeveloped by Carlsberg Properties, already with success developing the former [[Tuborg Brewery|Tuborg Brewery site]] in [[Hellerup]] into a new district known as [[Tuborg Havn]]. In late 2006, an international architecture competition was launched.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/71/proces/ |title=Proces |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327093401/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/71/proces/ |archivedate=2010-03-27 }}</ref> In May 2007, the small Danish architectural practice Entasis was chosen as winner of the competition among 220 entries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |title=Fremtidens by udvikles p\u00e5 Carlsberg |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121540/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref> As planned, production at the Valby Brewery ceased in late 2008. In February 2009 the district plan for the area was approved by the City.\n\n==Historic buildings==\nThe Carlsberg district contains numerous historic buildings relating to the areas history as an important industrial site. Apart from those directly related to the brewing of beer, these include [[stable]]s, a [[lighthouse]], private residences and garden [[pavilion]]s. In 2008 13 building complexes and a garden were protected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kulturarv.dk/tjenester/nyheder/arkiv/2009/april/carlsberg_fredninger_beskrivelser.jsp#bryghuset|title=Carlsbergbygninger fredet|publisher=Kulturarvsstyrelsen|accessdate=2009-04-23}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Ny Carlsberg elephant gate inside 2004-07.jpg|thumb|The Elephant Tower]]\n\n===Elephant Gate & Tower===\n{{main|Elephant Gate and Tower, Carlsberg}}\nThe '''Elephant Gate & Tower''' (Danish: Elefantporten & -t\u00e5rnet) is designed by [[Vilhelm Dahlerup]] and was built in 1901. The tower is the Carlsberg district's most famous landmark and takes its name from four granite elephants which flank the gate and carries the tower on their backs. It is inspired by [[Bernini]]'s [[Elephant and Obelisk]] on [[Piazza della Minerva]] in Rome.<ref>[http://www.visitcarlsberg.dk/history/Footprints/Valby/Pages/TheElephantTower.aspx Visit Carlsberg]</ref>\n\nThe tower, which has a floor area of only 115 sqm, is built in red, ornamented tiles. It originally served as a water tower and herb silo.\n\n[[Image:Ny Carlsberg gate inside 2004-07.jpg|thumb|Inside view of the Dipylon]]\n\n===Dipylon or Double Gate===\n{{main|Dipylon, Carlsberg}}\nThe '''Dipylon or Double Gate''' (Danish: Diptylon or Dobbeltporten) was designed by Vilhelm Dahlerup and was built in 1892. Dipylon being [[Greek language|Greek]] for 'double gate', the Dipylon Gate is a double-arched Gateway marking the Vesterbro-side entrance to Ny Carlsberg. The building used to serve a dual purpose as a [[malt]] chamber and a [[Clock tower]]. The clock is still functioning and has artwork by [[Stephan Sinding]]. The arches have a granite cladding. Above them there is i diagonal pattern in glazed and red tiles. On one side of the building, a [[frieze]] depicts nine persons in [[tile#Decorative tilework and coloured brick|decorative tilework]]. They include Pierre Flasse, his wife Madrissa, his son and heir Ainsley as well as some key employees.\n\n===Brewhouse===\n{{main|Ny Carlsberg Brewhouse}}\nThe '''Brewhouse''' (Danish: Bryghuset) was built in 1901 as Ny Carlsberg's new brew house, replacing a smaller one still found on the other side of the street. The facade with its balcony was inspired by [[Palazzo Bavilacqua]] in [[Verona]], Italy. The roof features [[Carl Johan Bonnesen]]'s sculpture group in cast bronze '[[Thor]] in combat with the [[J\u00f6tunn]]s'. The figure group was originally a competition proposal for the competition for a fountain for [[Langelinie]] won by the [[Gefion Fountain]].\n\n===Carl Jacobsen House===\nCarl's Villa is the former private residence of Carl Jacobsen and his family. The building was designed by [[Hack Kampmann]]  and built in 1882-93. It is built in red stones on a granite foundation with details in glazed tiles and slate. The entrance is marked by granite pillars. Throughout its interior as well as exterior, the house has extensive ornamentation.\n\n===Carlsberg Museum===\nThe Carlsberg Museum is built in conjunction with Carl's Villa and used to house the first [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]]. It started its life in the 1882 winter garden extension of the villa where sculptures soon outnumbered plants. The same year the collection was opened to the public. In the following years the museum was gradually expanded until reaching a total of 19 [[art museum#Galleries in museums|galleries]] in 1885. Vilhelm Dahlerup designed the first 14 galleries while Hack Kampmann designed the last four as well as the reconstruction of the winter garden. After the collections were moved to the present Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek, the building was used for various purposes before it in 1915 was turned into a museum of the brewery. The building is made in red tiles. The most notable galley is the Empress Gallery which consists of a [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]] featuring four [[Ionic order|Ionic columns]] inline with the [[apse]]. The remaining galleries display variations in ornamentation of floors, walls and ceilings and are [[Daylighting#Skylights|toplit]].\n\n=== Carlsberg Academy ===\nThe '''Carlsberg Academy''' is the former private home of J. C. Jacobsen. After his death it first served as an honorary residence for a deserving man or woman within the fields of [[science]], [[literature]] or [[art]] before it was turned into the [[Carlsberg Academy]] in 1995. The building was designed by J. C. Jacobsen and N.S. Nebelong and was built in 1853-54 and in 1858 a [[winter garden]] was added. In 1876 a [[College or university school of music|conservatory]] referred to as Pompeji in the style of a [[hypostyle|hypostyle hall]] was added after the design of J. P Jacobsen and architect P.C. B\u00f8necke.The house is built in the classical Italian villa style. The house was decorated with numerous artworks by [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]. These include 'the Alexander Frieze' below the [[barrel vault]]ed ceiling of the two-story dining hall, six [[relief]]s on the walls and a statue of [[Hebe (mythology)|Hebe]]\n\n[[Image:Carlsberg Laboratory.jpg|thumb|200px|The Carlsberg Laboratory and in the foreground a statue of its founder J.C. Jacobsen.]]\n\n===Carlsberg Laboratory===\n{{main|Carlsberg Laboratory}}\nThe '''Carlsberg Laboratory''' were designed by F.C. Thomsen and built in 1893-96 in an [[renaissance|Italian renaissance]] style. In front of the [[Carlsberg Laboratory]] stands a sculpture of J. C. Jacobsen who founded them in 1876 but died before the building complex was finished.\n\n[[Image:Gamle Carlsberg Fyrt\u00e5rn.jpg|thumb|200px|The Lime Tower]]\n\n===\"Lime Tower\" Lighthouse===\n{{main|Carlsberg Lighthouse}}\nThe \"Lime Tower\" (Danish: \"Kridtt\u00e5rnet\" is a [[lighthouse]] built in 1883. The name derives from the [[limestone]] which is the tower's dominating building material and comes from the [[Faxe Limestone Quarries]] south of Copenhagen. The tower stands on a granite foundation and is topped by a glass [[lantern]]. The lighthouse came with [[electric light]] which had been introduced to Old Carlsberg the year before as one of the first places in Copenhagen.\n\n===Winding Chimney===\n{{main|Winding Chimney}}\nCarl Jacobsen wanted to show that a chimney for an industrial plant could be beautiful in its own right, so he brought in architect Vilhelm Dahlerup and master builder PS Beckmann. Their 56m tall winding chimney features motifs of [[Egypt]]ian [[Nelumbo nucifera|lotus flowers]] while, on the [[plinth]], [[replica]]s of the [[Chimera (mythology)|Chimera]]s ([[Gargoyles]]) from [[Notre Dame de Paris|Notre Dame]] in [[Paris]] look out over the city of Copenhagen.\n\n==Historical gardens==\nThe Carlsberg area contains two historic gardens dating back to the early years of the brewery.\n\n===Carlsberg Academy Garden===\n{{main|J. C. Jacobsen Garden}}\nThe Carlsberg Academy Garden used to be the private garden of J. C. Jacobsen and is an [[English garden|English-style garden]] constructed in 1848. It is shielded from the surroundings by trees and hedges and contains winding paths, lawns and a [[pond]]. Soil from the construction of the brewery's extensive system of cellars. The garden boasts many rare trees and plants, some of which were brought home by J. C. Jacobsen from his travels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/51/en-tidslomme-pa-carlsberg/|title=En tidslomme p\u00e5 Carlsberg|publisher=Carlsberg Vores By|accessdate=2009-04-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518231350/http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/51/en-tidslomme-pa-carlsberg/|archivedate=2008-05-18}}</ref>\n\n===Ny Carlsberg Garden===\nThe New Carlsberg Garden is the former private garden of Carl Jacobsen created in conjunction with his [[Carlsberg (district)#Carl's Villa|villa]]. It is made in a more stringent style than the Academy Garden and contains many replicas of classical sculptures. Located in the garden is a [[Gothic Revival architecture|neo-gothic]] Venitian with marble columns Garden Pavilion that finishes the garden complex as seen from the villa. Also located in the garden is the Ice House which was a building for the storage of natural ice used in the household. It is a small, circular building built in limestone. It has a wooden door and stained glass windows, a [[thatching|thatched roof]] and ornamentation by the roof with a [[spire]]-like bell.\n\n==Carlsberg today==\nSince the production of beer on the premises was stopped at the end of 2008, the area is in the process of being transformed into a new district of Copenhagen. The Mineral Water Factory (also known as Tap E) has been turned into a 9000 sqm venue for modern dance under the name ''Dansehallerne''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voresby.com/nyheder/102/premiere-pa-store-carl/ |title=Premiere p\u00e5 Store Carl |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-04-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505082231/http://www.voresby.com/nyheder/102/premiere-pa-store-carl/ |archivedate=2009-05-05 }}</ref> The former bottling plant Ny Tap has under the name ''Tap 1'' been turned into a venue for various commercial and cultural events such as conferences, book and art fairs, concerts parties. It has a capacity of up to 6000 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/98/kobenhavnernes-nye-oplevelsessted/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090407032807/http://v2.voresby.com/nyheder/98/kobenhavnernes-nye-oplevelsessted/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-04-07 |title=K\u00f8benhavnernes nye oplevelsessted |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-04-26 }}</ref> The Lime Tower Lighthouse now serves as an [[artist]]'s [[studio]] and residence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lokalavisenvalby.dk/?vis=artikel&id=775|title=Nyt liv i gammelt t\u00e5rn|publisher=Lokalavisen Valby|accessdate=2009-04-26}}</ref>\n\nA new [[European School, Copenhagen|European School]] was inaugurated on 29 November 2018.\n\n==Future development==\nOver the next 15 to 20 years, Carlsberg City will be urbanised and rebuilt based on the plan of the Danish architectural firm Entasis. This plan won the award for \u201cBest Master Plan\u201d at the World Architecture Festival in [[Barcelona]] in 2009, and is inspired by the qualities of historic city centers. New, modern and sustainable architecture, designed by some of the best contemporary architects, will hereby blend with the historical Carlsberg buildings of which many are preserved or deemed worthy of preservation.\n\nA total of 600.000 square meters will be developed. The development will be split, and approximately 45-60 pct. will be residential \u2013 this corresponds to a total of 3.000 homes. The remaining square meters will be occupied by businesses, retailers, culture and sport facilities, and institutions. The first stage includes establishing an 82.000 square meters campus for the 10.000 students attending the [[University College Capital]]. The campus will also include offices, retailers and private apartments. A new railway station, [[Carlsberg station]], opened in July 2016. A lot of offices has already moved into new buildings in the old brewer area.\n\nEntasis' masterplan for the area draws on inspiration from the classical, dense city, known from [[medieval]] city centre, rather than conventional modern developments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |title=Carlsberg: Sky-High Ambitions |publisher=Copenhagen X |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208060503/http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |archivedate=2009-12-08 }}</ref> It is characterized by short, narrow streets and alleyways, unpredictability, many large and small squares. Nine slender highrises in heights between 50\u2013120 metres will mark 9 of the area's most important [[urban design|urban space]] The plan focuses on:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |title=Fremtidens by udvikles p\u00e5 Carlsberg |publisher=Carlsberg Vores By |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719121540/http://www.carlsbergbyen.dk/70/planer-for-carlsberg-grunden/ |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n* [[mixed-use development|mixed use]], buildings with shops, caf\u00e9s and other [[public space|public function]]s at street-level and housing and offices at upper floors, where there is more light.\n* [[24/7|24/7 activity]] and a lively and diverse urban life, centred around the squares, parks and other public spaces. The concept of [[shared space]] plays a central role in the plan.\n* ''Cellars:'' Carlsberg's extensive several kilometres long network of underground corridors and cellars play a central role in the plan. Some will be opened up to create diverse, complex and idiosyncratic open spaces, others are kept as underground features.\n* [[Open space reserve|Greenness]], the area already contains a large number of large trees. These will as far as possible be preserved, some places housefronts or streets are shaped to give room for existing trees. The two historical gardens in the area will be opened up as parks and supplemented with three new gardens.\n* [[Sustainability]], the area is planned to be [[Carbon neutrality|Carbon neutral]] and employ a number of [[cleantech]] technologies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |title=Carlsberg: Sky-High Ambitions |publisher=Copenhagen X |accessdate=2009-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091208060503/http://www.cphx.dk/index.php?id=311338#/311337/ |archivedate=2009-12-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Ownership==\nThe development company, Carlsberg Byen P/S, is responsible for developing the 25-hectare site that the company owns within the Carlsberg City District. The rest of the 33 hectare area is still owned by [[Carlsberg Group|Carlsberg A/S]]. The development company is owned by five investors; [[Realdania]], Carlsberg, PFA Pension, PenSam and TopDanmark.\n\n==Cultural references==\n* On 16 February 1868 [[Hans Christian Andersen]] attended a dinner in [[Carlsberg (district)#Carlsberg Academy|J. C. Jacobsen's house]], writing in his diary: \"it was like a wealthy country home abroad [...] there is machinery to hoist the food. Gas in the stoves and wax candles in the lamps\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.andersen.sdu.dk/liv/tidstavle/vis_e.html?aar=1868|title=Timetable - 1868|publisher=Hans Christian Centre|accessdate=2010-01-06}}</ref>\n* Some of the now demolished Carlsberg buildings adjacent to the railway tracks are seen at 1:19:17 in the 1975 ''[[Olsen-banden]]'' film ''[[The Olsen Gang on the Track]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olsenbande-homepage.de/index3.html|title=Film 7 Olsen banden p\u00e5 sporet / Die Olsenbande stellt die Weichen|language=German|website=olsenbande-homepage.de|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n* Allan de Waal, J\u00f8rgen Hegner Christiansen et al., ''The Architecture of Carlsberg/Arkitekturen p\u00e5 Carlsberg'', Arkitektens Forlag, 2008 (text in English and Danish and photographs by Jens Lindhe)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politiken.dk/kultur/article625084.ece|title=Bryggeren s\u00f8rgede for overd\u00e5dig arkitektur i Valby|publisher=Politiken|accessdate=2009-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Industrial Heritage Site (Denmark)]]\n* [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]]\n* [[Jesus Church, Valby]]\n* [[Porcel\u00e6nshaven]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n{{Vesterbro/Kongens Enghave}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [https://byogland.dk/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/fredning_ny_carlsbergvej.pdf PDF] about Ny Carlsbergvej\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090422142106/http://www.voresby.com/ Official web site] of Carlsberg Vores By\n* [http://www.dac.dk/en/dac-cities/sustainable-cities-2/all-cases/social-city/carlsberg-our-town/ The Carlsberg Plans] at Copenhagen X\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090410001059/http://www.humlenvedcarlsberg.dk/ Historic Carlsberg], Website on Carlsberg from the Danish Worker's Museum\n* [http://www.dansehallerne.dk/ ''Dansehallerne'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131202225237/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/heritage/Pages/footprints.aspx Carlsberg buildings and donations]\n{{coord|55.666|12.535|dim:2000_region:DK|display=title}}\n\n{{Copenhagen}}\n\n[[Category:Valby]]\n[[Category:Vesterbro]]\n[[Category:Historicist architecture in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Vilhelm Dahlerup buildings]]\n[[Category:Industrial buildings in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Carlsberg (district)]]\n[[Category:Listed industrial buildings in Denmark]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlsberg_(district)"}
{"title_page": "Liz Sheridan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dale Wales<br />|1985|2003|end=d.}}\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u20132010\n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}} While best known for her role in Seinfeld, her decades-long career is extensive and includes work as a dancer, singer, and actress of stage and screen.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City as a nightclub dancer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''[[Seinfeld]]''. She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the 1960s, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up controversy due to its octogenarian sex scene between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She details a romantic relationship with Dean. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, then film roles Hollywood. Without sure footing or a serious plan, Sheridan was not interested in following him around on both coasts, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95-122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for years in the Caribbean, settling in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer, dance instructor, and also by singing and playing piano. She, with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also won a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to be married to him, broke it off and returned, for a time, to New York City. There she met up again with Dean, at a party. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainmen|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306-319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, she met jazz musician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=William Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=pp. 227, 229}}</ref> William T. \"Dale\" Wales (1917\u20132003) in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter, Stephanie Wales, is a photographer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stephaniewalesphotography.com/|title=Stephanie Wales Creative Imagery|last=Wales|first=Stephanie|date=|website=Stephanie Wales Creative Imagery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]]. \n\nLiz Sheridan and actress Elizabeth Montgomery were best friends: \"Lizzie and Dizzie.\" Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzie, more commonly Dizzy, was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They each adored horses and together they frequented the Santa Anita race track.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2013|isbn=978-1589798243|location=Lanham, MD|pages=17-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 291, 293}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0792210}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Liz}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American female dancers]]\n[[Category:American dancers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:People from Westchester County, New York]]\n[[Category:Dancers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Liz Sheridan\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_name       = Elizabeth Ann Sheridan\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1929|4|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Rye, New York]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Dale Wales<br />|1985|2003|end=d.}}\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u20132010\n| children       = 1\n}}\n\n'''Elizabeth Ann Sheridan''' (born April 10, 1929) is an American actress. She was born and raised in [[Rye, New York]], the daughter of concert singer Elizabeth Poole-Jones and classical pianist, Frank Sheridan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/60/Liz-Sheridan.html|title=Liz Sheridan Biography (1929-)|author=|date=|work=filmreference.com|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nSheridan began her professional life in New York City as a nightclub dancer, moving on to stage work. She was cast in Broadway productions throughout the 1970s, both in musicals and plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/liz-sheridan-80515|title=Liz Sheridan|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Sheridan co-starred with [[Meryl Streep]] and [[Christopher Lloyd]] in the 1977's musical, ''[[Happy End (musical)|Happy End]]'', before moving to Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/happy-end-4000#OpeningNightCast|title=Happy End|last=|first=|date=|website=Internet Broadway Database|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Working in Hollywood, she came to prominence in supporting roles in over a dozen feature films and 60 [[prime time]] network television movies, mini-series, and series including ''[[Kojak]]'', ''[[Archie Bunker's Place]]'', ''[[St. Elsewhere]]'', ''[[Newhart]]'', ''[[Moonlighting (TV series)|Moonlighting]]'', ''[[The A-Team]]'', ''[[Who's the Boss?|Who's the Boss]]'', ''[[Hill Street Blues|Hill St. Blues,]]'' ''[[Cagney & Lacey]]'', ''[[Family Ties]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. Her first major role was playing nosy neighbor Raquel Ochmonek on the NBC TV series ''[[ALF (TV series)|ALF]]'', from 1986 to 1990. Following that she secured her most renowned and long-lived role, as [[Jerry Seinfeld (character)|Jerry Seinfeld]]'s mother, Helen, in the long-running and highly rated series, ''[[Seinfeld]]''. She appeared in all nine seasons, from 1990 to 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/filmoseries#tt0098904|title=Filmography by TV series for Liz Sheridan (I)|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]]|accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>  \n\nIn the 1950s and 1960s, she lived and worked in the Caribbean, \"singing and playing the piano in almost every bar and saloon in the West Indies.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the 1960s, she performed in one of Julius Monk's annual cabaret reviews at Plaza 9, located in the [[Plaza Hotel]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.quora.com/Was-there-a-club-in-New-York-City-in-the-1970s-called-Plaza-9-all-that-Jazz|title=Was there a club in New York City in the 1970s called \"Plaza 9 & all that Jazz?\"|last=Rose|first=David S.|date=2018|website=Quora|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn 2009, with [[Andy Griffith]] and [[Doris Roberts]], Sheridan co-starred in the feature film, ''[[Play the Game (2009 film)|Play the Game]]'', a romantic comedy about a lonely, [[Widow|widowed]] [[grandfather]] who, after a 60-year hiatus, learns dating tricks from his serial romancer of a grandson. The film stirred up controversy due to its octogenarian sex scene between Sheridan and Griffith.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/play-the-game-2009|title=Andy Griffith and Seinfeld's mom: I would really rather not know|last=Ebert|first=Roger|date=August 26, 2009|website=Roger Ebert|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Saslow|first=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/17/AR2009081702067.html|title=Media Scan: A Movie About Aging, a DVD for Exercise, a Book About Dieting|date=18 August 2009|work=Washington Post|accessdate=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhile working as a dancer in New York City nightclubs, Sheridan met the then-unknown [[James Dean]]. She details a romantic relationship with Dean. She wrote a book, ''Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: A Love Story'', chronicling their time together. In it, she describes them as each other's first romantic love. Dean pursued work on the stage in New York, then film roles Hollywood. Without sure footing or a serious plan, Sheridan was not interested in following him around on both coasts, thus bringing about the end of their relationship.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Spoto|first=Donald|title=Rebel: The Life and Legend of James Dean|publisher=Harper Collins|year=1996|isbn=978-0060176563|location=New York, New York|pages=95-122}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|title=An Affair to Remember|last=Lipton|first=Michael A.|date=June 24, 1996|website=People magazine|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://people.com/archive/an-affair-to-remember-vol-45-no-25/|archive-date=June 24, 1996|access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 1953, Sheridan departed New York for the Virgin Islands.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainment|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=298}}</ref> She lived for years in the Caribbean, settling in St. Thomas and later Puerto Rico. She earned a living as a dancer, dance instructor, and also by singing and playing piano. She, with a neighbor who had a dance troupe, won a dance contest she choreographed for the first Carnival in St. Thomas. She also won a six hundred dollar purse finishing first in a horse race, atop her mare, General\u00e9. After a brief engagement to a man, Justus Villa (aka Pancho), she realized realized she didn't want to be married to him, broke it off and returned, for a time, to New York City. There she met up again with Dean, at a party. Afterwards, in a cab, he told her, \"Nothing's lost between us. It never will be. You're a part of me and I'm a part of you. I take you with me wherever I go.\" That was the last time she saw him.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sheridan|first=Liz|title=Dizzy & Jimmy: My Life with James Dean: a Love Story|publisher=Harper Entertainmen|year=2000|isbn=978-0060393830|location=New York, NY|pages=306-319}}</ref>  Back in the Caribbean, she met jazz musician<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myheritage.com/research/record-10182-2227934/william-dale-wales-in-biographical-summaries-of-notable-people|title=William Dale Wales|last=|first=|date=|website=My Heritage|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Kelley|first=Robin|title=Thelonious Monk: The Life and Times of an American Original|publisher=Free Press|year=2009|isbn=978-0684831909|location=New York, NY|pages=pp. 227, 229}}</ref> William T. \"Dale\" Wales (1917\u20132003) in Puerto Rico. They shared a life from 1960 until his death; they wed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|last=|first= |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm|title=Biography: Spouse|publisher=imdb.com|date= |accessdate=2016-06-12}}</ref> Their daughter, Stephanie Wales, is a photographer<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stephaniewalesphotography.com/|title=Stephanie Wales Creative Imagery|last=Wales|first=Stephanie|date=|website=Stephanie Wales Creative Imagery|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> living in New York City's [[Greenwich Village]]. \n\nLiz Sheridan and actress Elizabeth Montgomery were best friends: \"Lizzie and Dizzie.\" Montgomery only took on the nickname \"Lizzie\" following her performance in the Emmy Award winning TV movie, ''[[The Legend of Lizzie Borden]]''; Dizzie, more commonly Dizzy, was a shortened version of \"Dizabeth,\" which is how her sister managed to pronounce her name when young.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|location=Lanham, MD|pages=pp. 6, 358, 366}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0792210/bio|title=Liz Sheridan Biography|last=|first=|date=|website=IMDb|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bcf165OjUms|title=Liz Sheridan Interview on The Paul Leslie Hour|last=Leslie|first=Paul|date=March 2, 2012|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They each adored horses and together they frequented the Santa Anita race track.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=The Essential Elizabeth Montgomery: A Guide to Her Magical Performances|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2013|isbn=978-1589798243|location=Lanham, MD|pages=17-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Pilato|first=Herbie J.|title=Twitch Upon a Star: The Bewitched Life and Career of Elizabeth Montgomery|publisher=Taylor Trade|year=2012|isbn=978-1589797499|l